
[1]innocent

   IN'NOCENT, a. [L.innocens.]

   1. Properly, not noxious; not producing injury; free from qualities
   that can injure; harmless; innoxious; as an innocent medicine or
   remedy.

   2. Free from guilt; not having done wrong or violated any law; not
   tainted with sin; pure; upright. In this general sense, no human being
   that is a moral agent, can be innocent. It is followed by of.

   3. Free from the guilt of a particular crime or evil action; as, a man
   is innocent of the crime charged in the indictment.

   4. Lawful; permitted; as an innocent trade.

   5. Not contraband; not subject to forfeiture; as innocent goods carried
   to a belligerent nation.

                 IN'NOCENT, n. One free from guilt or harm.

   1. A natural; an idiot. [Unusual.]
